name: TheAtlantic
text: Mindy Kaling's "Never Have I Ever"—along with "Selah and the Spades" and "The Half of It"—tells a story about a young woman of color who has the freedom to fumble her way through her teen years, @ethiopienne writes. https://t.co/awGSee7Rc6

name: TheAtlantic
text: "To defend Trump’s business holdings, however, the Justice Department has been forced to reinterpret its own opinions in the narrowest way possible," Jane Chong writes: https://t.co/RTHsV2nMrm

name: TheAtlantic
text: "We push away from what we know." How the work ethic of artists syncs with this moment of pandemic: https://t.co/LaBFmGib6L

name: TheAtlantic
text: "The insect is relentless in its search for hosts. Those who fight it must be relentless too." Sarah Zhang on the quietly audacious project that changed the lives of cattle, deer, and humans throughout North and Central America: https://t.co/76OFCG6cCs

name: TheAtlantic
text: "When a lone creep who refuses to wear a mask or stay home, being the 10th person to join a chant against the offender takes no courage; being the 10,000th to retweet a denunciation takes even less courage," @gcaw writes: https://t.co/I17ebZq3VZ

text: The sand may be safe, but what if Americans are too timid to return to shore towns and spend money? @russellberman looks at our upcoming Pandemic Summer: https://t.co/qtSBxTTem9

name: TheAtlantic
text: The pandemic is global, but lots of Americans don’t have any local news outlets telling them what’s happening in the communities where they actually live, Mark Bowden writes: https://t.co/KIpX6zei8v

name: TheAtlantic
text: The NASA astronauts that SpaceX will fly to space today have been training for this flight for more than four years. They’ve been best friends for over 20—and told @julieebeck their story: https://t.co/o2JtKQ5ub5

name: TheAtlantic
text: Two astronauts are about to embark on a historic mission to space that is designed, from start to finish, not by NASA, but by SpaceX, @marinakoren reports: https://t.co/imdjb35fLj

name: TheAtlantic
text: RT @abdallah_fayyad: "If all we know is that [racial] disparities exist—and that is indeed all we know—then prepare for racist explanations to rush in to fill the gap." -@gcaw: https://t.co/OL8Ozibe1m

name: TheAtlantic
text: “I will miss the end-of-the-world ebullience, the temporal beauty of live performance, like a monk’s sand painting; swept away at the end of the night, but held in memory, jewel-like,” @rosannecash writes: https://t.co/c9oeF28DKS

name: TheAtlantic
text: RT @NesimaAberra: I really enjoyed chatting with @amandamull for this new series, Behind the Byline, on Atlantic staffers and their work. Check out the interview here and see a cute photo of her dog, Midge: https://t.co/cClc0CDjFg

name: TheAtlantic
text: RT @marinakoren: "You’re just trying to be as normal as possible, really. We don’t want to focus a lot on, ‘Oh, this is the last time we’ll have dinner here. This is the last time we’ll watch this show.’" https://t.co/c52gumKeYe

name: TheAtlantic
text: In our new series "Behind the Byline," @amandamull shares what's on her mind, her favorite stories from her "Material World" column, and how she approaches her work. https://t.co/c1hpM5CzwY

text: "While Andrew Cuomo was benefiting from heart-string-tugging segments on CNN, his state was struggling … Journalism that truly aims to restore trust in media would hold Cuomo to account for these missteps," argues @GrahamDavidA: https://t.co/WScdvwvQgY

name: TheAtlantic
text: Americans can't stay in their homes forever. To get the most out of summer while staying safe, they'll have to use what researchers know about the coronavirus to assess the risk of everything from beach days to barbecues, writes @amandamull https://t.co/3IrWRHsbkt

name: TheAtlantic
text: Vann R. Newkirk II spent the better part of a year immersed in the stories of Hurricane Katrina’s victims and heroes. The project weakened his faith in America’s catastrophe preparedness. COVID-19, he writes, finally stripped him of his last illusions: https://t.co/RvvZzzIIyN
